        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat(talk): add macOS realtime relay mode",
        "body": "## Summary\n- add a provider-neutral macOS Talk realtime relay path backed by `talk.session.*` gateway RPCs\n- parse configured `talk.realtime` gateway-relay settings into a small relay descriptor\n- keep the existing macOS STT/TTS pipeline as fallback when no compatible realtime relay config is present\n- preserve typed relay tool payload/result values at the `AnyCodable` boundary\n- emit provider-neutral macOS relay proof markers for signed-app evidence capture\n- document macOS and Android realtime relay opt-in and fallback behavior\n\n## Validation\n- `git diff --check upstream/main...HEAD`\n- provider/config-specific source scan: no local provider, model, keychain, or user-specific strings in touched PR files\n- `swift test --package-path apps/macos --filter TalkModeGatewayConfigTests` passed locally: 4 tests, 0 failures\n- regression coverage confirms `talk.realtime.mode = realtime` without explicit `transport = gateway-relay` preserves the existing STT/TTS fallback path\n\n## Real Behavior Proof\nDeferred for this draft.\n\nI did not install, replace, or launch a source-built macOS app from this fork for proof. The local proof path is still not clean: `security find-identity -p codesigning -v` reports `0 valid identities found`, and no branch-built `dist/OpenClaw.app` is present.\n\nThis branch emits provider-neutral macOS relay log markers so a maintainer can capture signed/non-quarantined app proof without relying on local provider details. Public Talk docs now stay focused on runtime behavior and do not include maintainer proof/runbook details.\n\nThe maintainer proof still needs a clean signed app run showing relay session creation, microphone audio forwarding, assistant output audio receipt/playback, cancel or barge-in, and omitted-transport fallback. Unit tests, docs, and source checks above are supplemental only; this PR should stay draft until that real signed app run is captured or maintainers intentionally apply a proof override.\n",
